english:
  title: Preface to the Master of Three Peaks' Miscellaneous Critiques of Buddhism
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have long lamented how deeply Buddhism's teachings mislead the world. Thus I have said: Heaven is heaven, and humans are human—and herein lies the fundamental difference between Confucian and Buddhist doctrine.

    Since the advent of astronomical calculation, the cycles of cold and heat, the waxing and waning of sun and moon, all follow fixed patterns. These patterns prove reliable across ten thousand generations, revealing that heaven's nature is immutable. Therefore, Buddhism's notion of Mount Sumeru is but deception.

    Heaven employs yin and yang, the five elements, to generate all things. Yin, yang, and the five elements possess both principle and material force. Those who receive their fullness become human; those who receive their partiality become mere things. Thus the principle of the five elements manifests in humans as the five constant virtues, while their material force constitutes the five organs. This is the teaching of we Confucians. Physicians diagnose the organs and vessels using the five elements to discern disease. Diviners employ the five elements to gauge fortune's rise and fall. Used across ten thousand generations, all proves true. Therefore, humanity's essence is likewise fixed, and Buddhism's doctrine of the four elements is merely empty fantasy.

    Tracing back to origins: if we cannot understand how humans come to be, how can we fathom their passing? Thus the teaching of rebirth too lacks credibility.

    I have maintained this argument for years. Now, having read the Master of Three Peaks' Twenty Discussions Critiquing Buddhism, I find his treatment of rebirth, the five elements, medicine, and divination to be most lucid and complete. His other arguments are equally thorough, clear, and leave nothing to say further.

    Since youth, the Master has studied profoundly and nursed a burning conviction to practice his learning and refute heterodoxy. In every discussion, he argues tirelessly, and his students listen eagerly and follow. He once composed three essays on Heart, Material Force, and Principle to illumine the distinction between our Way and heterodox error, greatly benefiting the moral order. Meeting this enlightened court, he aids in the governance of our realm, and though his teachings have not been fully implemented, they have been substantially realized. Yet the Master's heart remains unsatisfied. He yearns to restore the virtue of Yao and Shun to rulers and people alike. Regarding heterodoxy, he grieves that he cannot wholly banish it. In the summer of the year jiawu, during a brief respite from illness, he created this work and showed it to me, saying:

    "Buddhism's poison destroys the bonds of human relationship and inevitably leads people toward bestiality, destroying humanity itself. Those who uphold the moral order must make it their enemy and attack it with force. I once believed that if circumstances favored me, I could sweep it away entirely. Now, blessed with the ruler's understanding and trust in my counsel, I thought I might achieve this. Yet still I cannot expel it—so perhaps it cannot be expunged. Consumed by indignation, I have written this work hoping future generations will heed it, that all people might understand. Thus I employ many humble examples, lest these teachings grow lax. Thus my words burn with fierce passion. Yet read this, and the distinction between Confucian truth and Buddhist falsehood becomes luminously clear. Though this age may not implement it, if it can be transmitted to posterity, I can die at peace."

    Reading this through, I could not rest from admiration and sighed: "When Yang Zhu and Mo Di blocked the true way, Mencius refuted them through words. When Buddhism entered China, its poison proved far more virulent than theirs. The earlier sages often refuted its errors, yet none achieved a lasting written work. Even Han Yu, possessed of great talent, was flanked by followers like Zhang Ji and Huang-fu Mi, yet dared not commit his arguments to text. How much less can those of lesser stature? Now the Master not only refutes with force and enlightens his contemporaries, but leaves a written legacy for posterity. His concern for the Way runs deep and far. People's delusion regarding Buddhism centers most upon its doctrines of death and life. The Master himself states: 'If I can refute Buddhism, I can die in peace'—wishing thus to free people from their delusion. His intention toward others is indeed profound and sincere. Mencius inherited the line of three sages; the Master too carries forward Mencius' legacy. What Zhang Zai called 'standing alone without fear, possessing singular integrity and self-trust, talents far exceeding ordinary men'—surely this describes the Master? I sincerely revere him and wish to study his way. Therefore I set down what I have long said, to verify it with him.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Mount Sumeru: In Buddhist cosmology, the central cosmic mountain believed to be the center of the universe. Gwon Geun argues this contradicts astronomical observation.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Five elements (오행): Wood, fire, earth, metal, and water—fundamental to both Confucian and Chinese medical philosophy.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Five constant virtues (오상): Benevolence, righteousness, propriety, wisdom, and trust—core to Confucian ethics.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Four elements (사대): In Buddhist philosophy, earth, water, fire, and wind as the material constituents of existence.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Master of Three Peaks (삼봉): Refers to Jeong Dojeon (정도전), a prominent Neo-Confucian scholar and statesman.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Yang Zhu and Mo Di: Ancient Chinese philosophers whose doctrines Mencius famously opposed.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Han Yu: Tang Dynasty Confucian scholar famous for his anti-Buddhist arguments.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Zhang Zai: Northern Song Neo-Confucian philosopher and founding figure of Li Xue (理學) philosophy.'
